webpackJsonp([0xaa7987f59c24],{1072:function(t,e){t.exports={data:{site:{siteMetadata:{title:"Psyked.co.uk",author:"James Ford"}},markdownRemark:{id:"/Users/James/Repositories/portfolio-2018/src/posts/actionscript-2-to-actionscript-3-communication-try-flashinterface/index.md absPath of file >>> MarkdownRemark",html:"<p>As you probably know, Actionscript 2 and Actionscript 3 projects aren't completely compatable - they can't be, what with all the changes under the hood.  Migrating your own coding techniques is hard enough, but migrating projects can be so much easier and nigh-on-impossible.  So, how could you make a mish-mash of Actionscript 2 and Actionscript 3 movies play nice?</p>\n<p>Well, there's a few solutions, and several classes that claim to do the job, but the best I've found is <a href=\"http://www.flashextensions.com/products/flashinterface/examples/01_flashinterface_avms.html\">FlashInterface</a>.  It might take a bit of figuring out at first, but the Events based model means that I find it quite easy to use.</p>\n<h2>Links</h2>\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"http://www.flashextensions.com/products/flashinterface/examples/01_flashinterface_avms.html\">FlashInterface demonstration</a>.</li>\n</ul>",frontmatter:{title:"Actionscript 2 to Actionscript 3 communication? try FlashInterface...",date:"August 20, 2008",tags:["external-links"],url:null}}},pathContext:{prev:{frontmatter:{path:"/blog/a-reason-why-photoshop-cs4-kicks-ass/",tags:null,title:"A reason why Photoshop CS4 kicks ass",image:null,date:"2009-01-28T09:02:54.000Z"}},next:{frontmatter:{path:"/blog/actionscript-2-xml-cdata-returns-undefined-or-htmltext-doesnt-work/",tags:["actionscript","flash","cdata","quirks","xml"],title:"ActionScript 2 - XML CDATA returns undefined, or htmlText doesn't work!",image:null,date:"2008-09-17T07:40:13.000Z"}}}}}});
